net.java.jddac.jmci.units
Class Dimension

java.lang.Object
  net.java.jddac.jmci.units.Dimension

public class Dimension
extends java.lang.Object

The type of a physical quantity, such as length. We can't measure a shoe, but we can measure its length, mass, capacitance, coefficient of thermal expansion, etc. All those things are dimensions. We (mostly) follow the recommendations of the SI

Which things are dimensions and which are not is a matter of engineering choice, not theory, and thus there is legitimate disagreement, and the boundaries are fuzzy. A dimension should be unambiguously definable and measurable (thus, comfort and romantic attraction are not dimensions). It should be widely useful (thus frogs/pond is not a dimension).

The SI dimensions are widely accepted, and are what we use here, but it helps to remember that the choices are not always clear-cut. Length is unambiguous and widely-used, but not all lengths are commensurate. In a column of pipe dimensions, if most are axial lengths, but one is a diameter, that may well be an error the programmer would like us to detect. If you multiply a window's height by its height, you don't get its area. The unit "fathom" is usually reserved for distances directed downward from sea level, and is incorrectly applied to other lengths. Etc. So length as used by the SI is a valid choice, but it is the superclass of a wide collection of entities which are distinguished in common practice.

On the other hand, the SI does make provision for many subclasses of what we might call "concentration." We find mass/mass concentration, mass/volume concentration, volume/volume concentration, molarity/volume concentration, and molarity/molarity concentration. Within each of these there are solute/solvent and solute/total distinctions. The point is that this is a matter of convention, and the boundaries are necessarily arbitrary. Therefore, almost any practical problem will want something slightly different from what is provided, and the practitioner will have some perfectly valid reason why his choice should be preferred. But we gain a huge benefit in interoperability when we agree on what we mean by, say, length. Therefore, no means is provided to extend the set of base dimensions.

The internal representation of dimensions is hidden, but it preserves arithmetic structure, e.g. speed is related correctly to length and time. When Unit.initialize(), it creates a set of base dimensions: LENGTH, MASS, TIME, CURRENT, TEMPERATURE, AMOUNT, INTENSITY, PLANE_ANGLE and SPHERICAL_ANGLE. All others can be created from these by multiplication and division.

A unit has a name. This can be assigned when it is created, or one can be derived (one name for the quotient of length and time is "length/time"). Names are useful to a Quantity package as the heading for columns, and the title of graphs (e.g. a graph whose x-axis is labelled in time units and whose y-axis is labelled in length units can be labelled as "speed").

PLANE_ANGLE

public static final Dimension PLANE_ANGLE
The dimension of plane angle. Considered by SI not to be a dimension at all, but a dimensionless ratio. Separated here because of its usefulness in distinguishing torque from energy, and in signalling a Quantity package that it should allow trigonometric operations.

SPHERICAL_ANGLE

public static final Dimension SPHERICAL_ANGLE
The dimension of spherical angle. Considered by SI not to be a dimension, but separated here for consistency with plane angle.

Construct a dimension from a signature. Name is required because we have no way of guessing.

Parameters:
exponents - exponents of base dimensions
isDimensionless - true if this is a "dimensionless" ratio with the given dimension in the numerator and denominator, e.g. volume/volume for concentration
nm - the name to give this dimension, e.g. "density"
Returns:
an existing dimension with those properties if one exists, otherwise a new dimension.

specialize

public static Dimension specialize(Dimension d,
                                   java.lang.String name)
Create a specialization of a dimension. A specialization behaves by default just like its parent, but is not equals() its parent. This allows a Quantity package to choose a subset of units for it (like restricting "fathoms" to distances below sea level), and to keep distinguish among different uses of a dimension (e.g. the length of a pipe vs. its diameter).

Parameters:
d - the dimension to be specialized
name - the name of this specialization. For example, LENGTH might have specializations with names "width", "height", "radius", etc. An exception is thrown if name is already in use.
Returns:
a new dimension.
